04640nam a22006255i 9780822392996DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223929967 a10.1515/97808223929962doi  a(DE-B1597)551857  a(OCoLC)1170099270  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aB825 7aPOL0100002bisacsh  aCC 60002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17650:00aNew Materialisms :bOntology, Agency, and Politics /cDiana Coole, Samantha Frost. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (347 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroducing the New Materialisms -- tA Vitalist Stopover on the Way to a New Materialism -- tNon-Dialectical Materialism -- tThe Inertia of Matter and the Generativity of Flesh -- tImpersonal Matter -- tFeminism, Materialism, and Freedom -- tFear and the Illusion of Autonomy -- tMaterialities of Experience -- tThe Politics of ''Life Itself '' and New Ways of Dying -- tThe Elusive Material, What the Dog Doesn't Understand -- tOrientations Matter -- tSimone de Beauvoir: Engaging Discrepant Materialisms -- tThe Materialism of Historical Materialism -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew Materialisms brings into focus and explains the significance of the innovative materialist critiques that are emerging across the social sciences and humanities. By gathering essays that exemplify the new thinking about matter and processes of materialization, this important collection shows how scholars are reworking older materialist traditions, contemporary theoretical debates, and advances in scientific knowledge to address pressing ethical and political challenges. In the introduction, Diana Coole and Samantha Frost highlight common themes among the distinctive critical projects that comprise the new materialisms. The continuities they discern include a posthumanist conception of matter as lively or exhibiting agency, and a reengagement with both the material realities of everyday life and broader geopolitical and socioeconomic structures.Coole and Frost argue that contemporary economic, environmental, geopolitical, and technological developments demand new accounts of nature, agency, and social and political relationships; modes of inquiry that privilege consciousness and subjectivity are not adequate to the task. New materialist philosophies are needed to do justice to the complexities of twenty-first-century biopolitics and political economy, because they raise fundamental questions about the place of embodied humans in a material world and the ways that we produce, reproduce, and consume our material environment.ContributorsSara AhmedJane BennettRosi BraidottiPheng CheahRey ChowWilliam E. ConnollyDiana CooleJason EdwardsSamantha FrostElizabeth GroszSonia KruksMelissa A. Orlie  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aAgent (Philosophy). 0aMaterialismxPolitical aspects. 0aMaterialism. 0aOntology. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBennett, Jane1 aCheah, Pheng1 aCoole, Diana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrost, Samantha, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrosz, Elizabeth1 aOrlie, Melissa A.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392996zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822392996423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822392996.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_